Airlines Fatalities

Introduction

In this project we are analyzing data collected from 1976 to 2001 about airline fatal accidents by the International Civil Aviation Organization in Montreal , Canada (www.icao.int).

Our goal is to get a good prediction about future fatalitis through a bayesian approach.

Our data is structured with four columns, year, fatal, miles, rate.

“Passenger miles” are in units of 10111011 and the “accident rate” is the number of fatal accidents per 10111011 passenger miles.

Following three descriptive time series plot respectively about the number of fatal accidents, the miles flown and the accident rate per each year.

I started with the simplest model i could immagine, that simply all the years look the same. This means that the number of fatal accidents in each year are independend with a Poisson(/theta) distribution. I set a non informative gamma prior distribution for θθ, that has (α,β)=(0.01,0.01)(α,β)=(0.01,0.01)

The model for the data is:

where /theta is the expected number of fatal accidents in an year. If the prior distribution for θθ is (Γ(α,β))(Γ(α,β)) then the posterior distrubution is Γ(α+ny¯,β+n)Γ(α+ny¯,β+n), where in this case n=26n=26 and ny¯=∑26i=1yi=634ny¯=∑i=126yi=634

yi|θ∼Poisson(θ)yi|θ∼Poisson(θ)

Posterior distribution

The posterior distribution for θθ is θ|y∼Γ(634,26)θ|y∼Γ(634,26) and the conditional distribution of y~y~ (the number of fatal accidents in 2002) is Poisson(θ)Poisson(θ).

So to simulate values of y~y~ all we need to do is first generate a realized value form the posterior distribution of θθ as the mean. Iterating this process will generate values of y~y~ from the posterior predictive distribution. What we are doing here is integrating numerically, using simulation, over the posterior distrobution in θθ. We can simulate this easily in R.

theta <- rgamma(1000, 634, 26 )
y.2002 <- rpois(1000,theta)
#hist( y.2002 )
plot( table(y.2002), type="h", lwd=5, lend=2, col=gray(0.5), bty="n", ylab="" )

We can specify the model in R using the package rJags.

a1.par <- c("mu","fatal[27]")

a1.ini <- list(list( mu=22 ),
              list( mu=23 ),
              list( mu=24 ) )

a1.dat <- list( fatal = c(airline$fatal,NA), I=27 )

# Model compilation and burn-in
a1.mod <- jags.model( file = "a1.jag",
                    data = a1.dat,
                    inits = a1.ini,
                    n.chains = 3,
                    n.adapt = 1000 )
## Compiling model graph
##    Resolving undeclared variables
##    Allocating nodes
## Graph information:
##    Observed stochastic nodes: 26
##    Unobserved stochastic nodes: 2
##    Total graph size: 30
## 
## Initializing model
# Sampling from the posterior
a1.res <- coda.samples( a1.mod,
                      var = a1.par,
                      n.iter = 10000,
                      thin = 10 )
summary( a1.res )
## 
## Iterations = 10:10000
## Thinning interval = 10 
## Number of chains = 3 
## Sample size per chain = 1000 
## 
## 1. Empirical mean and standard deviation for each variable,
##    plus standard error of the mean:
## 
##            Mean     SD Naive SE Time-series SE
## fatal[27] 24.37 4.9904  0.09111        0.09103
## mu        24.37 0.9703  0.01772        0.01772
## 
## 2. Quantiles for each variable:
## 
##            2.5%   25%   50%   75% 97.5%
## fatal[27] 15.00 21.00 24.00 28.00 35.00
## mu        22.48 23.73 24.38 25.02 26.25
print( xyplot( a1.res[,1:2] ) )

theta <- rgamma(6000, 634, 26 )
y.2002 <- rpois(6000,theta)
plot( table(y.2002), type="h", lwd=5, lend=2, col=gray(0.2), bty="n", ylab="", xlim=c(5,50) )
tpr <- table( as.matrix( a1.res[,"fatal[27]"] ) )
points( as.numeric(names(tpr))+0.4, tpr, type="h", col="red", lwd=4 )

###################
result = ggs(a1.res)
ggs_density(result)

ggs_traceplot(result)

ggs_running(result)

ggs_autocorrelation(result)

ggs_pairs(result) ########mmmmmeh
